        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Hi friends \xf0\x9f\x91\x8b ,
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Happy Monday!
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         On Mondays, I typically write deep dives on some of the most fascinating companies in the world. About once a month, though, I like to get a little wild, pick a trend, and work through its implications.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Last month, I wrote that
         <em>
          <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxVkMFuhSAQRb_msdMAIuqCRTf9DYMwKhHBwNgX_75UkzZNmJDMzcyde4xGWGK61BEzkjNDGp1VTPK-acVArBKW9W1PXB7nBLBr5xWmE8hxTt4ZjS6Ge4JS3pJVUd6J3gotYW6NBKM5n6bGdP2sQQrByI_PqE_rIBhQ8AXpigGIVyvikV_Nx4t_lhciTjG5sNT5nDJqs9Um7kU4SuU441snqFyuoJwQlgpXqHadNsBMnOKUU8YaykoI0dSslm1qLy8HKeAl6L7wf2tJUr9-Rd5WvYO_hZJyLP9-BofXCEFPHuwDAB9kdx68DlAB3tkDIqSnWahw2rNuYAMpbjYWeOHP6BtdL4JD" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
           Software is Eating the Markets
          </a>
         </em>
         . Today, I\xe2\x80\x99m exploring Remote Work, about which two things are true:
        </p>
        <ol style="margin: 1em 0;">
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           We talk about it a lot already.
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           Its potential impact is deeply underappreciated.
          </p>
         </li>
        </ol>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Remote Work will change everything.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Now let\xe2\x80\x99s get to it.
        </p>
        <div style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px;">
         <hr style="background: #e0ecf6; border: none; height: 1px; margin: 24px 0; padding: 0;"/>
        </div>
        <h1 style="color: #1a1a1a; font-family: 'SF Compact Display', -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, 'Apple Color Emoji', 'Segoe UI Emoji', 'Segoe UI Symbol'; font-size: 2em; font-weight: 700; line-height: 1.16em; margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0;">
         We\xe2\x80\x99re Never Going Back
        </h1>
        <div class="captioned-image-container-static" style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; text-align: center;">
         <figure style="display: inline-block; margin: 0 auto; width: 100%;">
          <table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="image-wrapper" style="margin: 1.6em auto; mso-padding-alt: 1em 0 1.6em;" width="100%">
           <tbody>
            <tr>
             <td style="text-align: center;">
             </td>
             <td align="left" class="content" style="text-align: center;" width="444">
              <a class="image-link" href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxVUcuO5CAM_JrmlohnAgcOo5X2NyIeThp1AlkgM5v5-qGTw2olhMtl2WW5nKmwpHzqPZWKjgJ5Cl6TgUomuEJec0-kkCiUac4AmwmrrvkAtB92Dc7UkOLVgTEV6Kmxd8PoxShmBlwIj7GcmZylFUoqohx660zm8AGiAw2fkM8UAa36WeteHuzjQX-353zsy2FLNe7Vu7Q1KmxmgRZnqO75jm1MTQ_6688N2MeSkm_5vE57TkuGUsInNL5UgL113BJUvEXEW6Z99nAvaPXcARbWOsk7awzrOBuhU4LIznjLqIVxVJL3hfVmM98pmq9y79Vm3Le44LVkuSDBymE-0I4IJTqOreykdGOn_CBHauwgrJoIV_wvYQL3e1xQ0BRTTAjDjeKc9aQfRBbnOqiBw4PjbaH_nQVlHVO1KYe4tPLraTZYr0LbaWpxO2Ko5wTR2BX8bV29zb6cqOcOOsJXWaFWyDfZ_KRYkrEZhpqaT832-E_oBz27ttk" style="border: none; display: block; height: auto; margin: 0; padding: 0; text-decoration: none; width: auto;" target="_blank">
               <img alt="" class="" data-attrs='{"src":"https://bucketeer-e05bbc84-baa3-437e-9518-adb32be77984.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/109c0462-1595-40b8-88c7-9d6872ab65b9_1494x1350.png","height":1316,"width":1456,"resizeWidth":444,"bytes":361532,"alt":null,"title":null,"type":"image/png","href":null}' src="https://cdn.substack.com/image/fetch/w_444,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fbucketeer-e05bbc84-baa3-437e-9518-adb32be77984.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F109c0462-1595-40b8-88c7-9d6872ab65b9_1494x1350.png" style="-ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic; border: none !important; display: block; height: auto; margin: 0 auto; margin-bottom: 0; max-width: 100%; vertical-align: middle; width: auto;" width="444"/>
              </a>
             </td>
             <td style="text-align: center;">
             </td>
            </tr>
           </tbody>
          </table>
         </figure>
        </div>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Admit it. When you first heard the news about the 90-95% effective vaccines, out loud you said:
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         \xe2\x80\x9cOh that\xe2\x80\x99s wonderful! Think of all the lives saved!\xe2\x80\x9d
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         While inside you were like:
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         \xe2\x80\x9cAh fuck.\xe2\x80\x9d
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         That doesn\xe2\x80\x99t make you a bad person. The selfish part of your brain has a faster reaction time than the good person part. And selfishly, for those lucky or privileged enough to have avoided losing loved ones to COVID and to be able to work from home, COVID has had some positives.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         The vaccine, for all its benefits, also means a few things you\xe2\x80\x99re not going to be happy about if you\xe2\x80\x99ve gotten used to the \xe2\x80\x9cnew normal.\xe2\x80\x9d Bye bye ready-made excuse for any social event you didn\xe2\x80\x99t
         <em>
          really
         </em>
         want to go to. Sweatpants are out, slacks are in. Hope you enjoyed spending time with your family, that\xe2\x80\x99s done. Gas up the car for your morning commute! It\xe2\x80\x99s time to go back to the office.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Or is it? In month one, two, three, or even maybe four of the pandemic, it was a foregone conclusion that once this whole thing was over, we would go right back to the office. Then, after people moved around, spent more time with family, set up their home offices, became adept at matching sweatpants with a presentable top, and got used to their 15-second commutes, that conclusion seems less foregone. And as people learned new routines, companies adopted new ways of working together. It\xe2\x80\x99s not perfect, but nothing ever is eight months in.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Now, a debate rages among three camps:
        </p>
        <div class="captioned-image-container-static" style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; text-align: center;">
         <figure style="display: inline-block; margin: 0 auto; width: 100%;">
          <table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="image-wrapper" style="margin: 1.6em auto; mso-padding-alt: 1em 0 1.6em;" width="100%">
           <tbody>
            <tr>
             <td style="text-align: center;">
             </td>
             <td align="left" class="content" style="text-align: center;" width="550">
              <a class="image-link" href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxVUcuO5CAM_JrmlohnAgcOo5X2NyIeThp1AlkgM5v5-qGTw2olhMu27LKqnKmwpHzqPZWKjgJ5Cl6TgUomuEJec0-kkCiUac4AmwmrrvkAtB92Dc7UkOI1gTEV6KkZJmoc5DwrpYBRZwkfRw9YEebZjC1680zm8AGiAw2fkM8UAa36WeteHuzjQX-353zsy2FLNe7Vu7S1UtjMAi3OUN3zHduamh70158bsI8lJd_yeZ32nJYMpYRPaPVSAfY2cVNQ8SYRb5r22cO9oPVzB1hY6yTvrDGs42yETgkiO-MtoxbGUUneF9abzXynaL7KfVfbcWtxwevIckGByeBB0E7Z2XYcqO2Ma8hxR7j1ikk5TIQP9G9D_R4XFDTFFBPSRGzqc9aTfhBZnOugBg4PjreF_qcKyjqmalMOcWnt19NssF6NdtLU4nbEUM8JorEr-Nu5ent9GVHPHXSEr7JCrZDvYrOTYklGRRRqbD411-M_oh-mQrgN" style="border: none; display: block; height: auto; margin: 0; padding: 0; text-decoration: none; width: auto;" target="_blank">
               <img alt="" class="wide-image" data-attrs='{"src":"https://bucketeer-e05bbc84-baa3-437e-9518-adb32be77984.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/5016de52-9bfb-4e2b-acfb-c4c14bd93886_1462x388.png","height":386,"width":1456,"resizeWidth":null,"bytes":null,"alt":null,"title":null,"type":null,"href":null}' src="https://cdn.substack.com/image/fetch/w_2912,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fbucketeer-e05bbc84-baa3-437e-9518-adb32be77984.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F5016de52-9bfb-4e2b-acfb-c4c14bd93886_1462x388.png" style="-ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic; border: none !important; display: block; height: auto; margin: 0 auto; margin-bottom: 0; max-width: 550px; vertical-align: middle; width: 100%;" width="550"/>
              </a>
             </td>
             <td style="text-align: center;">
             </td>
            </tr>
           </tbody>
          </table>
         </figure>
        </div>
        <ol style="margin: 1em 0;">
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           <strong>
            Return.
           </strong>
           In this camp are the old school businesses and new school businesses led by more conservative leaders who want their teams to get back to the office so they can get back to real work.
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           <strong>
            Remote.
           </strong>
           The organizationally bleeding-edge companies were remote-first or remote-friendly even before COVID, and many tech companies have announced that they plan to let their employees work from anywhere even after a vaccine.
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           <strong>
            Hybrid.
           </strong>
           This camp agrees that things won\xe2\x80\x99t be exactly the same, and their solutions range from \xe2\x80\x9cMaybe we\xe2\x80\x99ll let people work from home on Fridays!\xe2\x80\x9d to much more creative combinations. \xe2\x80\x9cHybrid\xe2\x80\x9d gets a bad rap because to date, it\xe2\x80\x99s meant \xe2\x80\x9cmost of us are in the office but some of you can be remote and Zoom in for meetings,\xe2\x80\x9d but I\xe2\x80\x99ll be referring to a more intentional type of Hybrid that treats everyone as a combination of Remote and in-person.
          </p>
         </li>
        </ol>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Missing from the debate is the fact that
         <strong>
          it\xe2\x80\x99s not
         </strong>
         <em>
          <strong>
           really
          </strong>
         </em>
         <strong>
          up to the companies to choose
         </strong>
         . Employees will ultimately make the decision. The best employees have more options now than ever before, and they\xe2\x80\x99re not going to work for companies that make them shave, get dressed, hop into a car or a crowded subway, and sit at a desk in an office five days a week with their headphones on trying to avoid distractions and get work done.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Choosing to Return to the way things were is like choosing not to adopt software a decade or two ago. It\xe2\x80\x99s an option, but one that will doom a company to mediocrity.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         The idea that Remote is coming and the role of the office is changing is not novel. Much ink has been spilled on the subject, both before and after the start of COVID (no one, I think, has written better on the topic than my friend
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUM1uhiAQfJqPo2ERrB449NLXMAhbJR-CgaWNb1_UQ5NNJtnJZH6sIVxTPvWRCrFaMM_eaRjE2Cs5Maelg1GNzJf5OyPuxgdNuSI76hK8NeRTvBWcC8U2LSaQg7JGKQmjU1wAB-N6dMK6pQfHLp_ZVOcxWtT4g_lMEVnQG9FRXv3nS3y1K3UpNvsFO5dTPlLAtbNpbwzzWnDBAXoOLaPsO-gGldUZhmmQ-JJ8X0V36cnY9yViWcdES8o-ro1-b2bHcBOtxNxwr9HTOWM0S0D39KNnkTsunQfqiL8lIBHm59lKCz7CxwQTa24utW3iv9EfGhR1Qg" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          Dror Poleg
         </a>
         ). Even Bill Gates recently
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkE2OgzAMhU_T7EAJBEoXWcxmroHyY6jVkCAnAXH7SdvFSJZt2fJ78md1hjXSpfaYMisJaEanxNhN_SAfzCnpxDRMDNO8EMCm0atMBdhejEerM8bwueC8G9hTDXchJmEmA8Nkl9E4LpcepJGjdnqBO3v7zLo4hGBBwQF0xQDMq2fOe7r1P7fut8Z5nu0JS6SytZHWOtErBKdr0_GO1yJETQa9b9b6Q2p2HRxsaBsbD3Q1Uwz6QCqpOSO9mkz6AN-YkjBASo3DFbP2VYShemsK0XNRv5Z9K9pxoOHy42OUcJN8W7s2FZOytq_Wxo2RCjGbSBjWun499Qb-s6hY5lq3EjBfMwRtPLgvsfxl_AGQrx1UgDN5yBnoO6wYOz6J-0M8WHVzsdIO_0Z_O4WSxw" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          predicted that
         </a>
         \xe2\x80\x9c30% of the days in the office will go away.\xe2\x80\x9d
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Generally, though, people are both
         <strong>
          overestimating
         </strong>
         the likelihood that companies will successfully Return to the office full-time and
         <strong>
          dramatically underestimating
         </strong>
         the first-, second-, and third-order impacts of Remote or Hybrid work.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         To help put that into context, we\xe2\x80\x99ll explore:
        </p>
        <ul style="margin: 1em 0;">
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           <strong>
            The Remote Hype Cycle.
           </strong>
           We all went Remote way too quickly. It\xe2\x80\x99ll get better.
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           <strong>
            The Risk of Return.
           </strong>
           The decision isn\xe2\x80\x99t up to employers, it\xe2\x80\x99s up to employees. Companies that try to force a Return will lose the talent war.
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           <strong>
            New Physical and Digital Solutions.
           </strong>
           Remote won\xe2\x80\x99t always mean Zoom, and the Office won\xe2\x80\x99t always mean sitting at a desk five days a week.
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           <strong>
            Implications of Remote and Hybrid Work.
           </strong>
           The shift to Remote and Hybrid is going to change everything from work itself to housing, gaming, fitness, and so much more.
          </p>
         </li>
        </ul>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         We\xe2\x80\x99re never going back to the way things were. Like any major dislocation, that presents massive opportunities for those who are prepared and is going to completely run over those who aren\xe2\x80\x99t. This essay doesn\xe2\x80\x99t have all of the answers. Instead, it\xe2\x80\x99s an exploration of the trend, new options, and some implications, and a wakeup call to get ahead of this and win the gold rush.
        </p>
        <h3 style="color: #1a1a1a; font-family: 'SF Compact Display', -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, 'Apple Color Emoji', 'Segoe UI Emoji', 'Segoe UI Symbol'; font-size: 1.375em; font-weight: 700; line-height: 1.16em; margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0;">
         <strong>
          The Remote Hype Cycle
         </strong>
        </h3>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         It always feels safer to bet on the status quo. We\xe2\x80\x99ve worked in offices for more than a century, and we\xe2\x80\x99ll work in offices again.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Partially, that\xe2\x80\x99s because the burden of proof is always on the new thing; fads come and go, but at any moment, the way things are is the likeliest suspect for the way things are going to be. Partially, it\xe2\x80\x99s because the new thing is clunky; of course it is, it\xe2\x80\x99s new. And partially, it\xe2\x80\x99s because all of the other things that will spring up around the new thing haven\xe2\x80\x99t sprung up yet.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Take the laptop. In a 1985
         <em>
          New York Times
         </em>
         piece titled \xe2\x80\x9c
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUEGOwyAMfE25bQQEknDgsJf9RkTAaVAJRGCaze-XtoeVLNsa2xrPWINwT_nSRypIaoE8e6fZwKdeCkWcFo5NciK-zGsG2I0PGnMFctQleGvQp_i-oJRLsumRGy6EHOXK3cDNOq7ODj2ohTuqlJHkxTOb6jxECxqekK8UgQS9IR7l1n_f-E-L8zy7eKHfoXQ27Q1hapKvwluiU0tLLT5CKa3FDb7gF2xF_4Svtn9UhNxtuAfiNaecMtZT1iSJvmPdILO8wqAGATdB9zvvSl0KGvt4cZGsY8IlZR_vbfzYzA7hPWia51b3Gj1eM0SzBHAfO_Bj4FsdXgfoCGcJgO2ND9g84nRio2KKNDaXmpXxn-gPYCaEtQ" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          The Executive Computer
         </a>
         ,\xe2\x80\x9d Erik Sandberg-Diment concludes a skeptical journey through various viewpoints on the laptop\xe2\x80\x99s potential by writing:
        </p>
        <blockquote style="border-left: 4px solid #67bdfc; margin: 1em 0;">
         <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0; margin-left: 1em;">
          <em>
           As the software that is capable of turning them into true satellite offices becomes refined, they will probably even be used - in fact, profitably so. But the real future of the laptop computer will remain in the specialized niche markets. Because no matter how inexpensive the machines become, and no matter how sophisticated their software, I still can't imagine the average user taking one along when going fishing.
          </em>
         </p>
        </blockquote>
        <div class="captioned-image-container-static" style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; text-align: center;">
         <figure style="display: inline-block; margin: 0 auto; width: 100%;">
          <table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="image-wrapper" style="margin: 1.6em auto; mso-padding-alt: 1em 0 1.6em;" width="100%">
           <tbody>
            <tr>
             <td style="text-align: center;">
             </td>
             <td align="left" class="content" style="text-align: center;" width="248">
              <a class="image-link" href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxVUcuOrCAQ_Zpmp-GpuGDRmeT-huFR2qQVHMCZ63z9oC5ubkKow6lUnaKO1QXmmA61xVzQniGN3inSUckEH5BT3BEpJPJ5nBLAqv2iStoBbbtZvNXFx3BVYEwFeilHugFEbybpgE0TBWCSdBig7wcyTBM6dUa9Ow_BgoIvSEcMgBb1KmXLD_Z80D_1WBfavJtctH23Nq6V8queocYJin2dsbYp8UE_Pm_AnnOMrr6nZdxSnBPk7L-g8rkAbLXilqDiFBGnTL3Mbt9Q86kBLIyxkjdGa9Zw1kMzCCIb7Qyj5vyA5G1mrV71Twz6O99z1R73Li54DZkv2BPirKmtJLih4ZbzRkrbN85aMUxS9JUaKZd_Ce7bLczIK4opJoRhUpfPWUvaTiRxLN3QcXhwvM70v6WgpEIsJiYf5pp-v_QKy5WoE401rnvw5RghaLOAu40rt9WXD-XYQAX4zguUAukmq5sUS3L6haqai9X08E_oF1MWuFw" style="border: none; display: block; height: auto; margin: 0; padding: 0; text-decoration: none; width: auto;" target="_blank">
               <img alt="" class="" data-attrs='{"src":"https://bucketeer-e05bbc84-baa3-437e-9518-adb32be77984.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/711dcba3-8ed9-4c44-88c7-dcc59f8574c4_248x107.png","height":107,"width":248,"resizeWidth":null,"bytes":null,"alt":null,"title":null,"type":null,"href":null}' src="https://cdn.substack.com/image/fetch/w_248,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fbucketeer-e05bbc84-baa3-437e-9518-adb32be77984.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F711dcba3-8ed9-4c44-88c7-dcc59f8574c4_248x107.png" style="-ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic; border: none !important; display: block; height: auto; margin: 0 auto; margin-bottom: 0; max-width: 100%; vertical-align: middle; width: auto;" width="248"/>
              </a>
             </td>
             <td style="text-align: center;">
             </td>
            </tr>
           </tbody>
          </table>
         </figure>
        </div>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         It\xe2\x80\x99s hard to blame him. Desktop computers and floppy disks were the norm. Laptops were clunky. And the whole ecosystem of wifi, lithium-ion batteries, coffee shops, cloud-based software, and the millions of other things that combine to make laptops useful wasn\xe2\x80\x99t yet in place. A laptop was a poor substitute for the real thing.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Those in the Return camp think that, like the laptop, remote work will be for specialized niche companies, not the average one. They\xe2\x80\x99re wrong, but it\xe2\x80\x99s hard to blame them, either. Remote work today isn\xe2\x80\x99t very good.
        </p>
        <ul style="margin: 1em 0;">
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           <strong>
            Remote is new.
           </strong>
           Before the pandemic, only GitLab really did it at any meaningful scale.
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           <strong>
            Remote is clunky.
           </strong>
           Sitting at your kitchen table all day with kids screaming in your ear while you hop on the 7th Zoom call of the day, which is, by the way, a depressing Zoom Happy Hour, is a terrible experience.
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           <strong>
            Remote\xe2\x80\x99s ecosystem is underdeveloped.
           </strong>
           We\xe2\x80\x99ve had to shoehorn pre-Remote solutions to fit a new paradigm, and the impending wave of new tools hasn\xe2\x80\x99t yet arrived.
          </p>
         </li>
        </ul>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Because of the biggest exogenous shock to the system in decades, Remote work, which can be viewed comprehensively as a technology, hasn\xe2\x80\x99t gotten the chance to methodically work its way through the Adoption S-Curve. Instead, like
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxVUM2OhCAMfprhNgZQFA4c5rKvYRCqkkEwUHfj2y-ryW42adOkX9rvxxqEJeVT76kgOQrk0TvNei5b0SnidOeYFJL4Ms4ZYDM-aMwHkP2YgrcGfYrXBaVckFUrykC1_dwKUB0YOg8OrBpmSaXpp0GSH57RHM5DtKDhE_KZIpCgV8S9PNrXg3_UigmnlH1cmnJMBY19NzZtFdhrp_VZotmfxGtOOWWspazK7dqGNb3I4gy96jt4dHRb-L8HJOvfzxV-r2aDcAHVz1jndkSP5wjRTAHcbRXvcC7leO6gI3yVAIiQ72X1z6lkg2KKVDaXakzxj-gbgDV5Ow" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          Snapchat
         </a>
         , Laptops, and Bitcoin, it\xe2\x80\x99s going through one of my favorite frameworks: the Gartner Hype Cycle.
        </p>
        <div class="captioned-image-container-static" style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; text-align: center;">
         <figure style="display: inline-block; margin: 0 auto; width: 100%;">
          <table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="image-wrapper" style="margin: 1.6em auto; mso-padding-alt: 1em 0 1.6em;" width="100%">
           <tbody>
            <tr>
             <td style="text-align: center;">
             </td>
             <td align="left" class="content" style="text-align: center;" width="550">
              <a class="image-link" href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxVUcuO5CAM_JrmlohnQg4cRivtb0QG3GnUCWSBzGzP1w-dHFYrIVy2ZZdV5aDikvLL7KlUchTMc_CGDVwLJSfijfRMK01Cme8ZcYOwmpoPJPth1-CghhTPCUq5Ig8jBqTa6dEJfrdsHJExqtiEcuDAgDny5pnh8AGjQ4OfmF8pIlnNo9a93MTHjf9uz_nYl8OWCu7Zu7S1UthgwRbvWN3jHduamm78158LiI8lJd_y-zrvOS0ZSwmf2OqlIu5t4qLg6k2i3jTts4d7YuvnDqmy1mnZWQDRSTFiNymmO_BWcIvjOGnZF9HDBt8pwle57mo7Li1OeB5ZTigY56MddTdN0ndSwdDZJkvnwXmQQlKp-cwGSv-qtniPCwmGU04ZE5Q19aXoWT-orF7rMA0Sb5JuC_9PFZJNTNWmHOLS2s8HbLiejXbS3OJ2xFBfM0awK_rLuXp5fRpRXzuaiF9lxVoxX8VmJ6eajRObSGPzqbke_xH9ALKqtvU" style="border: none; display: block; height: auto; margin: 0; padding: 0; text-decoration: none; width: auto;" target="_blank">
               <img alt="" class="wide-image" data-attrs='{"src":"https://bucketeer-e05bbc84-baa3-437e-9518-adb32be77984.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/31227b78-994d-45a6-bc32-dacda4340482_1600x584.png","height":531,"width":1456,"resizeWidth":null,"bytes":null,"alt":null,"title":null,"type":null,"href":null}' src="https://cdn.substack.com/image/fetch/w_2912,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fbucketeer-e05bbc84-baa3-437e-9518-adb32be77984.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F31227b78-994d-45a6-bc32-dacda4340482_1600x584.png" style="-ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic; border: none !important; display: block; height: auto; margin: 0 auto; margin-bottom: 0; max-width: 550px; vertical-align: middle; width: 100%;" width="550"/>
              </a>
             </td>
             <td style="text-align: center;">
             </td>
            </tr>
           </tbody>
          </table>
         </figure>
        </div>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         COVID triggered a rush to remote work, and proponents quickly prophesied a remote-only future in which everyone lives and works from anywhere -- the Peak of Inflated Expectations. As the reality set in -- Zoom fatigue, kids at home, loss of social connection with co-workers -- remote fell into the Trough of Disillusionment. Remote and Hybrid skeptics point at the shortcomings and say, \xe2\x80\x9cSee, it might work for
         <em>
          some
         </em>
         companies, but not
         <em>
          every
         </em>
         company, not serious ones like ours.\xe2\x80\x9d
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Now, with a post-COVID world in view thanks to the vaccine, and faced with the possibility of having to put real pants back on, we\xe2\x80\x99re hitting the Slope of Enlightenment, which is defined as 1) the point at which the benefits begin to crystallize, 2) second and third generation products emerge, and 3) some enterprises pilot solutions while the most conservative remain skeptical. Check, check, check.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         The manifold benefits of Remote or Hybrid are beginning to crystallize, a few of which are:
        </p>
        <ul style="margin: 1em 0;">
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           <strong>
            No Commute.
           </strong>
           People spend nearly one stressful hour commuting every day. That\xe2\x80\x99s time they could be sleeping, working out, hanging with their kids, or even doing more work. Now that we\xe2\x80\x99ve lived without commutes, it\xe2\x80\x99s hard to imagine going back.
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           <strong>
            Live Anywhere.
           </strong>
           Not going to the office every day expands the choices for where to live. In Hybrid companies, employees might be able to live in the country two hours outside of the city and go in once or twice a week. Remote employees can live anywhere they desire, with anyone. Location will no longer be tied to employment.
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           <strong>
            Increase Opportunity and Access.
           </strong>
           Only .01% of the people in the world live in San Francisco, but a disproportionate amount of great jobs were based there. Now, the best people anywhere in the world can find their dream job without leaving their friends and families.
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           <strong>
            Find Better Talent.
           </strong>
           The flip side of the above is that companies who look globally can access the best talent in the world, regardless of where they happened to be born.
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           <strong>
            More Time With Family and Friends.
           </strong>
           Out of necessity and that magic that binds people going through a challenge together, people accepted that their co-workers were also going to be the people they spent the most time with: eight-plus hours in the office together, five days per week, plus happy hours. Remote will unbundle work and social.
          </p>
         </li>
        </ul>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Importantly, all but the most conservative companies understand that they will at least need to be Hybrid, if not fully Remote, not because they want to, but because the best people want to.
        </p>
        <h3 style="color: #1a1a1a; font-family: 'SF Compact Display', -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, 'Apple Color Emoji', 'Segoe UI Emoji', 'Segoe UI Symbol'; font-size: 1.375em; font-weight: 700; line-height: 1.16em; margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0;">
         <strong>
          The Risk of Return
         </strong>
        </h3>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Typically, it\xe2\x80\x99s safe for companies or people to wait until a technology gets a little bit further up the Slope of Enlightenment before deciding whether or not to adopt it. Competitors might move a little faster in the short term, but they could always adopt the new thing next year and be OK.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Companies don\xe2\x80\x99t have that luxury with remote work. Those who force their teams back into the office risk losing their most valuable resource: their most highly-sought-after employees.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         In a May
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkEGOhCAQRU_T7DCACrpgMZu5hkEslTSCgbKNtx-0F5NUQqV-qF__WYOwxHTpPWYkR4Y0uElzKbq6bXoy6WbiXdsRl4c5AWzGeY3pALIfo3fWoIvh-cGYaMmqWyX5KGY7q65WvaytYkqqTo0WoDY9J7fPYI7JQbCg4QPpigGI1yvinl_1z0v8ljrPs8L1lheobNzKSHAh-061pc3e2De1EGlGOE1COh6IkGYHfqIulPbj4KSbsynmOCNNsEUEesb0ps9Sa0pepwUTjPOa8RK3qSteyTa1l5e9bODVsG0RVT7GjMXvPoMkHSKOMbmwFPm9mg38IxQeQ3m3Izi8Bghm9DB9UeEX7pMcrx10gDN7uA_-Dgs_wTquet6T4jbFgjn8G_0BPMmQ0Q" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          interview with The Verge
         </a>
         , Slack CEO and Not Boring hero, Stewart Butterfield, responded to a question about how he\xe2\x80\x99s planning to organize the company geographically:
        </p>
        <div class="captioned-image-container-static" style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; text-align: center;">
         <figure style="display: inline-block; margin: 0 auto; width: 100%;">
          <table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="image-wrapper" style="margin: 1.6em auto; mso-padding-alt: 1em 0 1.6em;" width="100%">
           <tbody>
            <tr>
             <td style="text-align: center;">
             </td>
             <td align="left" class="content" style="text-align: center;" width="550">
              <a class="image-link" href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxVUcuO5CAM_JrmlohnAgcOo5X2NyIeThp1AlkgM5v5-qGTw2olhMu27Cq5nKmwpHzqPZWKjgJ5Cl6TgUomuEJec0-kkCiUac4AmwmrrvkAtB92Dc7UkOI1gTEV6KnnUTrrpBJKGM6BCJDMD0QMTlqsxhG9eSZz-ADRgYZPyGeKgFb9rHUvD_bxoL_bcz725bClGvfqXdpaKWxmgRZnqO75jm1NTQ_6688N2MeSkm_5vE57TkuGUsIntHqpAHubuCmoeJOIN0377OFe0Pq5Ayxsk847awzrOBuhU4LIznjLqIVxVJL3hfVmM98pmq9y62o77ltc8BJZLugxKEOl68hsfMelapsJHjsvHMfESM6ImMiA8V8-Dv0eFxQ0xRQTwjBp1-esJ_0gsjjXQQ0cHhxvC_3vKijrmKpNOcSltV9Ps8F6NZqkqcXtiKGeE0RjV_C3c_X2-jKinjvoCF9lhVoh38VmJ8WSjIoo1Nh8aq7Hf0Q_NbW3Sw" style="border: none; display: block; height: auto; margin: 0; padding: 0; text-decoration: none; width: auto;" target="_blank">
